<p> For this I will use a TEXT it looks like this<br>
input type="TEXT" value="" <br>
The value is what is in the solid text in the input tag IE. <br>
input type="TEXT" value="How to HTML"<br>
This is what it looks like<br>
<input type="text" value="How to HTML"><br>
Now all we need is a submit it looks like this again without the angle brakets </p><br>
input type="submit" value="Submit Question" IE.<br>
<br>
<input type="submit" value="Submit"><br>
<p>The entire thing has to be put into the form tag, it looks like this...<br>
</p>
<form>
<input type="text" value="How to HTML"><br>
<input type="submit" value="Submit Question">
</form> 
<p> The last thing we are going to look at for this section is the checkbox or the radio forms..<br>
form<br>
  input type="radio" name="htmlSkill" value="Good" <br>
  input type="radio" name="htmlSkill" value="Still Learning" 
/form<br>
It looks like this </p>
<form>
  <input type="radio" name="htmlSkill" value="Good"> Good <br>
  <input type="radio" name="htmlSkill" value="Still Learning"> Still Learning
</form>

<center><big><h1>PART THREE (Basic CSS (Cascading Style Sheets))</h1></big></center>

<p> Welcome to the CSS portion of my "tutorial"<br>
CSS is used to style a website or animate using "addons" like webkit<br>
You open the tag by calling the html tag and id here is an example<br>
<br>
H1 {<br>
<br>
}<br>
<br>
In between the { } lines is where you put attributes to style html tags a list can be found here<br>http://www.w3schools.com/cssreF/ <br> <br>

Div {<br>
 text-align: center;
 font-family: "Comic Sans MS", cursive, sans-serif;
<br>
}<br>
<br>
Make sure to end each attribute with ;<br>
